# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ordinal-arithmetic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] In the mathematical field of set theory, **ordinal arithmetic** includes binary operations on ordinal numbers such as addition, multiplication, and exponentiation.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Each can be defined in two different ways: either by constructing an explicit well-ordered set that represents the result of the operation or by using transfinite recursion.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] In addition to these standard operations for ordinals, there are also the "natural" arithmetic operations, which are usually described using the Cantor normal form for ordinals, and nimber operations.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The standard arithmetic operations and natural arithmetic operations on the finite ordinals are the same as the corresponding operations on the counting numbers, but arithmetic operations on the infinite ordinals are more complicated.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The sum of two well-ordered sets S and T is the ordinal representing the variant of lexicographical order with least significant position first, on the union of the Cartesian products *S* × {0} and *T* × {1}.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] This way, every element of S is smaller than every element of T, comparisons within S keep the order they already have, and likewise for comparisons within T.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The definition of ordinal addition *α* + *β* can also be given by transfinite recursion on β.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] When the right addend *β* = 0, addition gives *α* + 0 = *α* for any α.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] For *β* > 0, the value of *α* + *β* is the smallest ordinal strictly greater than the sum of α and δ for all *δ* < *β*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Ordinal addition on the natural numbers is the same as standard addition.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The first transfinite ordinal is ω, the set of all natural numbers, followed by *ω* + 1, *ω* + 2, etc.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The ordinal *ω* + *ω* is obtained by two copies of the natural numbers ordered in the usual fashion and the second copy completely to the right of the first.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] This is different from ω because in ω only 0 does not have a direct predecessor while in *ω* + *ω* the two elements 0 and 0′ do not have direct predecessors.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Ordinal addition is, in general, not commutative.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] For example, 3 + *ω* = *ω* since the order relation for 3 + *ω* is 0 < 1 < 2 < 0′ < 1′ < 2′ < ..., which can be relabeled to ω.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] In contrast *ω* + 3 is not equal to ω since the order relation 0 < 1 < 2 < ... < 0′ < 1′ < 2′ has a largest element (namely, 2′) and ω does not (ω and *ω* + 3 are equipotent, but not order-isomorphic).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Ordinal addition is still associative; one can see for example that (*ω* + 4) + *ω* = *ω* + (4 + *ω*) = *ω* + *ω*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Ordinal addition is left-cancellative: if *α* + *β* = *α* + *γ*, then *β* = *γ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Furthermore, one can define left subtraction for ordinals *β* ≤ *α*: there is a unique γ such that *α* = *β* + *γ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Nor does right subtraction, even when *β* ≤ *α*: for example, there does not exist any γ such that *γ* + 42 = *ω*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] If the ordinals less than α are closed under addition and contain 0, then α is occasionally called a γ-number (see *Additively indecomposable ordinal*).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] These are exactly the ordinals of the form *ω**β*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The Cartesian product, *S* × *T*, of two well-ordered sets S and T can be well-ordered by a variant of lexicographical order that puts the least significant position first.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Effectively, each element of T is replaced by a disjoint copy of S.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The order-type of the Cartesian product is the ordinal that results from multiplying the order-types of S and T.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The definition of ordinal multiplication can also be given by transfinite recursion on β.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] When the right factor *β* = 0, multiplication gives *α* · 0 = 0 for any α.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] For *β* > 0, the value of *α* · *β* is the smallest ordinal greater than or equal to (*α* · *δ*) + *α* for all *δ* < *β*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] which has the same order type as *ω* + *ω*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] and after relabeling, this looks just like ω.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Thus, *ω* · 2 = *ω* + *ω* ≠ *ω* = 2 · *ω*, showing that multiplication of ordinals is not in general commutative, c.f. pictures.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] As is the case with addition, ordinal multiplication on the natural numbers is the same as standard multiplication.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Multiplication of ordinals is not in general commutative.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Specifically, a natural number greater than 1 never commutes with any infinite ordinal, and two infinite ordinals α and β commute if and only if *α**m* = *β**n* for some nonzero natural numbers m and n.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The relation "α commutes with β" is an equivalence relation on the ordinals greater than 1, and all equivalence classes are countably infinite.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] There is a left cancellation law: If *α* > 0 and *α* · *β* = *α* · *γ*, then *β* = *γ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] A left division with remainder property holds: for all α and β, if *β* > 0, then there are unique γ and δ such that *α* = *β* · *γ* + *δ* and *δ* < *β*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Right division does not work: there is no α such that *α* · *ω* ≤ *ω**ω* ≤ (*α* + 1) · *ω*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The ordinal numbers form a left near-semiring, but do *not* form a ring.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Hence the ordinals are not a Euclidean domain, since they are not even a ring; furthermore the Euclidean "norm" would be ordinal-valued using the left division here.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] A δ-number (see *Additively indecomposable ordinal § Multiplicatively indecomposable*) is an ordinal β greater than 1 such that *α* ⋅ *β* = *β* whenever 0 < *α* < *β*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] These consist of the ordinal 2 and the ordinals of the form *β* = *ω**ω**γ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The definition of exponentiation via order types is most easily explained using Von Neumann's definition of an ordinal as the set of all smaller ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Then, to construct a set of order type *α**β* consider the set of all functions *f* : *β* → *α* such that *f*(*x*) = 0 for all but finitely many elements *x* ∈ *β* (essentially, we consider the functions with finite support).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] This set is ordered lexicographically with the least significant position first: that is, we write *f* < *g* if and only if *f*(*x*) < *g*(*x*) for the value *x* = max{*y* | *f*(*y*) ≠ *g*(*y*)}.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] This is a well-ordering and its order type is an ordinal number, *α**β*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The definition of ordinal exponentiation can also be given by transfinite recursion on the exponent β.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] When the exponent *β* = 0, exponentiation gives *α*0 = 1 for any α, including *α* = 0.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] For *β* > 0, the value of *α**β* is the smallest ordinal greater than or equal to *α**δ* · *α* for all *δ* < *β*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Both definitions simplify considerably if the exponent β is a finite number: *α**β* is then just the product of β copies of α; e.g.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] *ω*3 = *ω* · *ω* · *ω*, and the elements of *ω*3 can be viewed as triples of natural numbers, ordered lexicographically with least significant position first.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] This agrees with the ordinary exponentiation of natural numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] But for infinite exponents, the definition may not be obvious.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] For example, *α**ω* can be identified with a set of finite sequences of elements of α, properly ordered.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The equation 2*ω* = *ω* expresses the fact that finite sequences of zeros and ones can be identified with natural numbers, using the binary number system.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] This expression corresponds to the function *f* : *β* → *α* which sends *b**i* to *a**i* for *i* = 1, ..., *k* and sends all other elements of β to 0.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] While the same exponent notation is used for ordinal exponentiation and cardinal exponentiation, the two operations are quite different and should not be confused.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The cardinal exponentiation *A**B* is defined to be the cardinal number of the set of *all* functions *B* → *A*, while the ordinal exponentiation *α**β* only contains the functions *β* → *α* with finite support, typically a set of much smaller cardinality.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] To avoid confusing ordinal exponentiation with cardinal exponentiation, one can use symbols for ordinals (e.g. ω) in the former and symbols for cardinals (e.g. ℵ0) in the latter.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Jacobsthal showed that the only solutions of *α**β* = *β**α* with *α* ≤ *β* are given by *α* = *β*, or *α* = 2 and *β* = 4, or α is any limit ordinal and *β* = *ε* ⋅ *α* where ε is an ε-number larger than α.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] There are ordinal operations that continue the sequence begun by addition, multiplication, and exponentiation, including ordinal versions of tetration and other hyperoperations.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The degenerate case *α* = 0 occurs when *k* = 0 which requires there be no βs nor cs.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] This decomposition of α is called the **Cantor normal form** of α, and can be considered the base-ω positional numeral system.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The highest exponent *β*1 is called the degree of *α*, and satisfies *β*1 ≤ *α*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The equality *β*1 = *α* applies if and only if *α* = *ω**α*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] In that case Cantor normal form fails to express the ordinal in terms of smaller ones; this can happen as explained below.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] To compare two ordinals written in Cantor normal form, first compare *β*1, then *c*1, then *β*2, then *c*2, and so on.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] At the first occurrence of inequality, the ordinal that has the larger component is the larger ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] If they are the same until one terminates before the other, then the one that terminates first is smaller.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The ordinal *ε*0 (epsilon nought) is the set of ordinal values *α* of the finite-length arithmetical expressions of Cantor normal form that are hereditarily non-trivial where non-trivial means *β*1 < *α* when 0 < *α*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] It is the smallest ordinal such that *ε*0 = *ω**ε*0, i.e. in Cantor normal form the exponent is not smaller than the ordinal itself.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The ordinal *ε*0 is important for various reasons in arithmetic (essentially because it measures the proof-theoretic strength of the first-order Peano arithmetic: that is, Peano's axioms can show transfinite induction up to any ordinal less than *ε*0 but not up to *ε*0 itself).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] If *β′* = *β* one can apply the distributive law on the left and rewrite this as *ω**β*(*c* + *c′*), and if *β′* < *β* the expression is already in Cantor normal form).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] A variation of Cantor normal form is to set all the numbers *c**i* equal to 1 and allow the exponents to be equal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] In other words, every ordinal number *α* can be uniquely written as *ω**β*1 + *ω**β*2 + ⋯ + *ω**β**k*, where k is a natural number, and *β*1 ≥ *β*2 ≥ ... ≥ *β**k* ≥ 0 are ordinal numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Another variation of the Cantor normal form is the "base δ expansion", where ω is replaced by any ordinal *δ* ≥ 2 and the coefficients satisfy 1 ≤ *c**i* < *δ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Ernst Jacobsthal showed that the ordinals satisfy a form of the unique factorization theorem: every nonzero ordinal can be written as a product of a finite number of prime ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] This factorization into prime ordinals is in general not unique, but there is a "minimal" factorization into primes that is unique up to changing the order of finite prime factors (Sierpiński 1958).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] A prime ordinal is an ordinal greater than 1 that cannot be written as a product of two smaller ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] As discussed above, the Cantor normal form of ordinals below *ε*0 can be expressed in an alphabet containing only the function symbols for addition, multiplication and exponentiation, as well as constant symbols for each natural number and for ω.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] We can do away with the infinitely many numerals by using just the constant symbol 0 and the operation of successor, *S* (for example, the natural number 3 may be expressed as *S*(*S*(*S*(0))).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] This describes an *ordinal notation*: a system for naming ordinals over a finite alphabet.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] This particular system of ordinal notation is called the collection of *arithmetical* ordinal expressions, and can express all ordinals below *ε*0, but cannot express *ε*0.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] There are other ordinal notations capable of capturing ordinals well past *ε*0, but because there are only countably many finite-length strings over any finite alphabet, for any given ordinal notation there will be ordinals below *ω*1 (the first uncountable ordinal) that are not expressible.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Such ordinals are known as large countable ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The operations of addition, multiplication and exponentiation are all examples of primitive recursive ordinal functions, and more general primitive recursive ordinal functions can be used to describe larger ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The **natural sum** and **natural product** operations on ordinals were defined in 1906 by Gerhard Hessenberg, and are sometimes called the **Hessenberg sum** (or product) (Sierpiński 1958).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The natural sum of α and β is often denoted by *α* ⊕ *β* or *α* # *β*, and the natural product by *α* ⊗ *β* or *α* ⨳ *β*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The natural sum and product are defined as follows.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The natural sum and product are commutative and associative, and natural product distributes over natural sum.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] We have $\underbrace {\alpha \oplus \cdots \oplus \alpha } _{n}=\alpha \otimes n$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Natural sum and product are not continuous.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] For example, if natural sum were continuous then lim*n*<*ω* (1 ⊕ *n*) = 1 ⊕ *ω*, but the left-hand side equals ω and the right-hand side equals *ω* + 1.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Similarly, if natural product were continuous lim*n*<*ω* (2 ⊗ *n*) = 2 ⊗ *ω*, but the left-hand side equals ω and the right-hand side equals (*ω*0 + *ω*0) ⊗ *ω*1 = *ω*1 + *ω*1 = *ω* · 2.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The natural sum and product are the same as the addition and multiplication (restricted to ordinals) of John Conway's field of surreal numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The natural operations come up in the theory of well partial orders; given two well partial orders *S* and *T*, of types (maximum linearizations) *o*(*S*) and *o*(*T*), the type of the disjoint union is *o*(*S*) ⊕ *o*(*T*), while the type of the direct product is *o*(*S*) ⊗ *o*(*T*).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] A useful application of this is when α and β are both subsets of some larger total order; then their union has order type at most *α* ⊕ *β*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] If they are both subsets of some ordered abelian group, then their sum has order type at most *α* ⊗ *β*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] We can also define the natural sum *α* ⊕ *β* by simultaneous transfinite recursion on α and β, as the smallest ordinal strictly greater than the natural sum of α and γ for all *γ* < *β* and of γ and β for all *γ* < *α*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Similarly, we can define the natural product *α* ⊗ *β* by simultaneous transfinite recursion on α and β, as the smallest ordinal γ such that (*α* ⊗ *δ*) ⊕ (*ε* ⊗ *β*) < *γ* ⊕ (*ε* ⊗ *δ*) for all *ε* < *α* and *δ* < *β*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Also, see the article on surreal numbers for the definition of natural multiplication in that context; however, it uses surreal subtraction, which is not defined on ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The natural sum is associative and commutative.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] It is always greater or equal to the usual sum, but it may be strictly greater.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] For example, the natural sum of ω and 1 is *ω* + 1 (the usual sum), but this is also the natural sum of 1 and ω.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The natural product is associative and commutative and distributes over the natural sum.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The natural product is always greater or equal to the usual product, but it may be strictly greater.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] For example, the natural product of ω and 2 is *ω* · 2 (the usual product), but this is also the natural product of 2 and ω.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Under natural addition, the ordinals can be identified with the elements of the free commutative monoid generated by the gamma numbers *ω**α*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Under natural addition and multiplication, the ordinals can be identified with the elements of the free commutative semiring generated by the delta numbers *ω**ω**α*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The ordinals do not have unique factorization into primes under the natural product.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] has two incompatible expressions as a natural product of polynomials with non-negative coefficients that cannot be decomposed further.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] There are arithmetic operations on ordinals by virtue of the one-to-one correspondence between ordinals and nimbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Three common operations on nimbers are nimber addition, nimber multiplication, and minimum excluded value (mex).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] Nimber addition is a generalization of the bitwise exclusive or operation on natural numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cantor-normal-form] The mex of a set of ordinals is the smallest ordinal *not* present in the set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] In mathematics, a **cardinal number**, or **cardinal** for short, is a kind of number that measures the cardinality of a set, i.e., how many elements there are in a set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Cardinality is defined in terms of bijective functions.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Two sets have the same cardinality if, and only if, there is a one-to-one correspondence (bijection) between the elements of the two sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The cardinality of a finite set can be identified with a natural number, which can be found simply by counting its elements.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The behavior of cardinalities of infinite sets is more complex.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] However, a fundamental theorem due to Georg Cantor shows that it is possible for two infinite sets to have different cardinalities, and in particular the cardinality of the set of real numbers ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ is greater than the cardinality of ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The cardinality of ⁠ $\mathbb {N}$ ⁠ is usually denoted by ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠ (aleph-null), since it is the smallest aleph number.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The properties of other aleph numbers and of infinite cardinal numbers in general depend on statements independent of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory, such as the axiom of choice and the continuum hypothesis.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] For example, all infinite cardinal numbers are aleph numbers if and only if the axiom of choice is true.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Cardinality is studied for its own sake as part of set theory.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] It is also a tool used in branches of mathematics including model theory, combinatorics, abstract algebra and mathematical analysis.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] In category theory, the cardinal numbers form a skeleton of the category of sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] A natural number can be used for two purposes: to describe the size of a set, or to describe the position of an element in a sequence.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] These two notions diverge when generalized to infinite sets and sequences, with the position aspect leading to ordinal numbers, and the size aspect leading to cardinal numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] When considering the size of a set, the identities of individual members should be *abstracted away*; changing these individual members should not affect the size of the set, as long as they remain distinct from each other.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] For example, the set ⁠ $\{1,2,3\}$ ⁠ has three elements, so when one replaces its members following the mapping ⁠ $\{1\mapsto 4,2\mapsto 5,3\mapsto 6\}$ ⁠, the resulting set ⁠ $\{4,5,6\}$ ⁠ still has three elements.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] It is reasonable to further postulate that two sets ⁠ X ⁠ and ⁠ Y ⁠ have the same size if *and only if* such a mapping—a bijection—exists from ⁠ X ⁠ to ⁠ Y ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] This is exactly how the formal concept of cardinality is defined.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Sameness of cardinality is an equivalence relation.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] It is sometimes referred to as *equipotence*, *equipollence*, or *equinumerosity*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] It is thus said that two sets with the same cardinality are, respectively, *equipotent*, *equipollent*, or *equinumerous*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Every equivalence class of sets under equinumerosity corresponds to a cardinal number.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] For finite sets, cardinal numbers defined this way agree with the intuitive notion of numbers of elements (as a natural number), but infinite sets exhibit more complex behaviors.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] This is a bijection between the sets ⁠ $\{1,2,3,...\}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\{2,3,4,...\}$ ⁠, and thus they have the same cardinality ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠, despite the second being a proper subset of the first.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Therefore the intuition that the size of a proper subset of ⁠ X ⁠ is always strictly less than the size of ⁠ X ⁠ is usually only valid for finite sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] However, Cantor's diagonal argument shows that the power set operation always results in a strictly greater cardinality, allowing one to construct a larger cardinal number from any infinite cardinal number.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] For example, it can be shown that the cardinality of the set of real numbers is equal to ⁠ $2^{\aleph _{0}}$ ⁠, and thus there are strictly more real numbers than natural numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The cardinality function is a cardinal function that takes in a set A and returns its cardinal number: ⁠ $A\mapsto \vert A\vert$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] However, it is somewhat difficult to define "cardinal number" formally, especially for infinite sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Therefore, cardinal numbers are not usually thought of in terms of their formal definition, but immaterially in terms of their arithmetic/algebraic properties.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The only fundamental requirement on a cardinality function $A\mapsto |A|$ is: $A\sim B\iff |A|=|B|.$ The assumption that there is *some* function that satisfies this requirement is sometimes called the *axiom of cardinality* or *Hume's principle*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] It will be shown later that such a function can be constructed without the need to define it axiomatically.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] An alternative approach is to define an equality relation for cardinal numbers ⁠ $=_{c}$ ⁠ that may be different from the equality relation for sets, and use ⁠ $=_{c}$ ⁠ to develop the theory of cardinality.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Specifically, Moschovakis defines a (weak) **cardinal assignment** as an operation ⁠ $A\mapsto \vert A\vert$ ⁠ that satisfies ⁠ $A\sim \vert A\vert$ ⁠ (with the motivation that the cardinality of ⁠ A ⁠ should be represented by an "abstract" object ⁠ $\vert A\vert$ ⁠ that is equinumerous to ⁠ A ⁠).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The relation ⁠ $=_{c}$ ⁠ is then the same as the equinumerosity relation ⁠ $\sim$ ⁠ between sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] If a cardinal assignment *also* satisfies ⁠ $A\sim B\iff \vert A\vert =\vert B\vert$ ⁠, then it is a **strong cardinal assignment**.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] This ordinal number ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠ is also known as the **initial ordinal** of the cardinal number ⁠ $\vert X\vert$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] When ⁠ X ⁠ is a finite set, all possible well-orderings of ⁠ X ⁠ has the same order type; conversely, all finite ordinals have different cardinalities, and thus all finite ordinals are initial ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Under their respective von Neumann representations, both finite ordinals and finite cardinals are identified with von Neumann natural numbers, and cardinal and ordinal arithmetic (addition, multiplication, power, proper subtraction) give the same answers for finite numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] On the other hand, many different infinite ordinal numbers can have the same cardinality.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] For example, the first infinite ordinal ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠ has the same cardinality as ⁠ $\omega +1$ ⁠, ⁠ $\omega ^{2}$ ⁠, ⁠ $\omega ^{\omega }$ ⁠, $\epsilon _{0}$ ..., all of which are countable ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Among these, only ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠ itself is an initial ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The $\alpha$ -th infinite initial ordinal is written $\omega _{\alpha }$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Its cardinality is written $\aleph _{\alpha }$ (the $\alpha$ -th aleph number).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] For example, ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠ is also written as ⁠ $\omega _{0}$ ⁠, and its cardinality (the cardinality of any countable set) as ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The von Neumann cardinal assignment identifies $\omega _{\alpha }$ with $\aleph _{\alpha }$ , but the notation $\aleph _{\alpha }$ is used for writing cardinals, and $\omega _{\alpha }$ for writing ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] This is important because arithmetic on cardinals is different from arithmetic on ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] For example, $2^{\omega }=\omega <\omega ^{2}$ in ordinal arithmetic while $2^{\aleph _{0}}>\aleph _{0}=\aleph _{0}^{2}$ in cardinal arithmetic, even though under the von Neumann cardinal assignment ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠ are represented by the same set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Infinite initial ordinals are limit ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] So as an ordinal, an infinite initial ordinal is an extremely strong kind of limit.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] If the axiom of choice is not assumed, then a different approach is needed.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The oldest definition of the cardinality of a set *X* (implicit in Cantor and explicit in Frege and *Principia Mathematica*) is as the class [*X*] of all sets that are equinumerous with *X*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] This does not work in ZFC or other related systems of axiomatic set theory because if *X* is non-empty, this collection is too large to be a set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] In fact, for *X* ≠ ∅ there is an injection from the universe into [*X*] by mapping a set *m* to {*m*} × *X*, and so by the axiom of limitation of size, [*X*] is a proper class.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The definition does work however in type theory and in New Foundations and related systems.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] However, if we restrict from this class to those equinumerous with *X* that have the least rank, then it will work (this is a trick due to Dana Scott: it works because the collection of objects with any given rank is a set).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Some sources use a mixed definition between von Neumann cardinals and Scott cardinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] For example, Lévy defines ⁠ $\vert X\vert$ ⁠ as the von Neumann cardinal when ⁠ X ⁠ is well-orderable, and as the Scott cardinal otherwise.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] This convention retains the convenience provided by the von Neumann representation for studying *well ordered cardinals*, which is still a significant part of cardinal study even when the axiom of choice is not assumed.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Formally, the order among cardinal numbers is defined as follows: |*X*| ≤ |*Y*| means that there exists an injective function from *X* to *Y*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The axiom of choice is equivalent to the statement that given two sets *X* and *Y*, either |*X*| ≤ |*Y*| or |*Y*| ≤ |*X*|.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] A set *X* is called *Dedekind-infinite* if there exists a proper subset *Y* of *X* with |*X*| = |*Y*|, and Dedekind-finite if such a subset does not exist.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The finite cardinals are just the natural numbers, in the sense that, by definition, a set *X* is finite if and only if |*X*| = |*n*| = *n* for some natural number *n*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] It can be proven (without the axiom of choice) that any Dedekind-infinite set is infinite.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Assuming the axiom of choice, it can be proved that the Dedekind notions correspond to the standard ones.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The aleph numbers are the cardinalities of well-orderable infinite sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] They are denoted with the Hebrew letter $\aleph$ (aleph) marked with a subscript indicating their rank among aleph numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Since aleph numbers can be identified with their initial ordinals, they form a transfinite sequence: $\aleph _{0}=|\mathbb {N} |,\;\aleph _{1},\;\aleph _{2},\;\ldots ,\;\aleph _{\alpha },\;\ldots .$ For every ordinal ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠, there exists an aleph number ⁠ $\aleph _{\alpha }$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] If the axiom of choice is true, then *all* sets are well-orderable (by the well-ordering theorem), and thus all infinite cardinal numbers are aleph numbers, i.e., this transfinite sequence is in fact the list of all infinite cardinal numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] If the axiom of choice is not true (see Axiom of choice § Independence), then there exist sets that are not well-orderable, and thus infinite cardinals that are not aleph numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Such a cardinal must be incomparable to some aleph number by Hartogs's theorem, so in this case it is impossible to write all cardinal numbers in a totally ordered sequence.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] We can define arithmetic operations on cardinal numbers that generalize the ordinary operations for natural numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] It can be shown that for finite cardinals, these operations coincide with the usual operations for natural numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Furthermore, these operations share many properties with ordinary arithmetic.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] If the axiom of choice holds, then every cardinal *κ* has a successor, denoted *κ*+, where *κ*+ > *κ* and there are no cardinals between *κ* and its successor.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] (Without the axiom of choice, using Hartogs' theorem, it can be shown that for any cardinal number *κ*, there is a minimal cardinal *κ*+ such that $\kappa ^{+}\nleq \kappa .$ ) For finite cardinals, the successor is simply *κ* + 1.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] For infinite cardinals, the successor cardinal differs from the successor ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] If *X* and *Y* are disjoint, addition is given by the union of *X* and *Y*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] If the two sets are not already disjoint, then they can be replaced by disjoint sets of the same cardinality (e.g., replace *X* by *X*×{0} and *Y* by *Y*×{1}).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Zero is an additive identity *κ* + 0 = 0 + *κ* = *κ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Addition is commutative *κ* + *μ* = *μ* + *κ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Assuming the axiom of choice, addition of infinite cardinal numbers is easy.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Assuming the axiom of choice and, given an infinite cardinal *σ* and a cardinal *μ*, there exists a cardinal *κ* such that *μ* + *κ* = *σ* if and only if *μ* ≤ *σ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] It will be unique (and equal to *σ*) if and only if *μ* < *σ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The product of cardinals comes from the Cartesian product.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Zero is a multiplicative absorbing element: *κ*·0 = 0·*κ* = 0.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] There are no nontrivial zero divisors: *κ*·*μ* = 0 → (*κ* = 0 or *μ* = 0).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] One is a multiplicative identity: *κ*·1 = 1·*κ* = *κ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Multiplication is commutative: *κ*·*μ* = *μ*·*κ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Assuming the axiom of choice, multiplication of infinite cardinal numbers is also easy.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Thus the product of two infinite cardinal numbers is equal to their sum.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Assuming the axiom of choice and given an infinite cardinal *π* and a non-zero cardinal *μ*, there exists a cardinal *κ* such that *μ* · *κ* = *π* if and only if *μ* ≤ *π*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] It will be unique (and equal to *π*) if and only if *μ* < *π*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] where *XY* is the set of all functions from *Y* to *X*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] It is easy to check that the right-hand side depends only on ${|X|}$ and ${|Y|}$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] 2|*X*| is the cardinality of the power set of the set *X* and Cantor's diagonal argument shows that 2|*X*| > |*X*| for any set *X*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] This proves that no largest cardinal exists (because for any cardinal *κ*, we can always find a larger cardinal 2*κ*).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] In fact, the class of cardinals is a proper class.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Using Kőnig's theorem, one can prove *κ* < *κ*cf(*κ*) and *κ* < cf(2*κ*) for any infinite cardinal *κ*, where cf(*κ*) is the cofinality of *κ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Assuming the axiom of choice and, given an infinite cardinal *κ* and a finite cardinal *μ* greater than 0, the cardinal *ν* satisfying $\nu ^{\mu }=\kappa$ will be $\kappa$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Assuming the axiom of choice and, given an infinite cardinal *κ* and a finite cardinal *μ* greater than 1, there may or may not be a cardinal *λ* satisfying $\mu ^{\lambda }=\kappa$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] However, if such a cardinal exists, it is infinite and less than *κ*, and any finite cardinality *ν* greater than 1 will also satisfy $\nu ^{\lambda }=\kappa$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The logarithm of an infinite cardinal number *κ* is defined as the least cardinal number *μ* such that *κ* ≤ 2*μ*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Logarithms of infinite cardinals are useful in some fields of mathematics, for example in the study of cardinal invariants of topological spaces, though they lack some of the properties that logarithms of positive real numbers possess.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The continuum hypothesis (CH) states that there are no cardinals strictly between $\aleph _{0}$ and $2^{\aleph _{0}}.$ The latter cardinal number is also often denoted by ${\mathfrak {c}}$ ; it is the cardinality of the continuum (the set of real numbers).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Similarly, the generalized continuum hypothesis (GCH) states that for every infinite cardinal $\kappa$ , there are no cardinals strictly between $\kappa$ and $2^{\kappa }$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Both the continuum hypothesis and the generalized continuum hypothesis have been proved to be independent of the usual axioms of set theory, the Zermelo–Fraenkel axioms together with the axiom of choice (ZFC).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Indeed, Easton's theorem shows that, for regular cardinals $\kappa$ , the only restrictions ZFC places on the cardinality of $2^{\kappa }$ are that $\kappa <\operatorname {cf} (2^{\kappa })$ , and that the exponential function is non-decreasing.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The notion of cardinality, as now understood, was formulated by Georg Cantor, the originator of set theory, in 1874–1884.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Cantor noted that there is a bijection between two finite sets if and only if they have the same number of elements, and applied this concept of bijection to infinite sets (for example the set of natural numbers **N** = {0, 1, 2, 3, ...}).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Thus, he called all sets having a bijection with **N** *denumerable (countably infinite) sets*, which all share the same cardinal number.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] He called the cardinal numbers of infinite sets transfinite cardinal numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Cantor proved that any unbounded subset of **N** has the same cardinality as **N**, even though this might appear to run contrary to intuition.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] He also proved that the set of all ordered pairs of natural numbers is denumerable; this implies that the set of all rational numbers is also denumerable, since every rational can be represented by a pair of integers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] He later proved that the set of all real algebraic numbers is also denumerable.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] In his 1874 paper "On a Property of the Collection of All Real Algebraic Numbers", Cantor proved that there exist higher-order cardinal numbers, by showing that the set of real numbers has cardinality greater than that of **N**.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] His proof used an argument with nested intervals, but in an 1891 paper, he proved the same result using his ingenious and much simpler diagonal argument.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] The new cardinal number of the set of real numbers is called the cardinality of the continuum and Cantor used the symbol ${\mathfrak {c}}$ for it.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] Cantor formulated the continuum hypothesis in 1878.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/cardinal-number] In 1940, Kurt Gödel showed that the continuum hypothesis cannot be disproved from ZFC, and in 1963, Paul Cohen showed that it cannot be proved from ZFC either, establishing its independence.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] In mathematics, the **epsilon numbers** are a collection of transfinite numbers whose defining property is that they are fixed points of an **exponential map**.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] Consequently, they are not reachable from 0 via a finite series of applications of the chosen exponential map and of "weaker" operations like addition and multiplication.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] The original epsilon numbers were introduced by Georg Cantor in the context of ordinal arithmetic; they are the ordinal numbers *ε* that satisfy the equation $\varepsilon =\omega ^{\varepsilon },$ in which ω is the smallest infinite ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] The ordinal *ε*0 is still countable, as is any epsilon number whose index is countable.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] Uncountable ordinals also exist, along with uncountable epsilon numbers whose index is an uncountable ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] The smallest epsilon number *ε*0 appears in many induction proofs, because for many purposes transfinite induction is only required up to *ε*0 (as in Gentzen's consistency proof and the proof of Goodstein's theorem).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] Many larger epsilon numbers can be defined using the Veblen function.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] A more general class of epsilon numbers has been identified by John Horton Conway and Donald Knuth in the surreal number system, consisting of all surreals that are fixed points of the base-ω exponential map *x* → *ω**x*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] His gamma numbers are those of the form *ω**β*, and his delta numbers are those of the form *ω**ω**β*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] From this definition, it follows that for any fixed ordinal *α* > 1, the mapping $\beta \mapsto \alpha ^{\beta }$ is a normal function, so it has arbitrarily large fixed points by the fixed-point lemma for normal functions.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] When $\alpha =\omega$ , these fixed points are precisely the ordinal epsilon numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] Generally, the epsilon number $\varepsilon _{\beta }$ indexed by any ordinal that has an immediate predecessor $\beta -1$ can be constructed similarly.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] In particular, whether or not the index β is a limit ordinal, $\varepsilon _{\beta }$ is a fixed point not only of base ω exponentiation but also of base δ exponentiation for all ordinals $1<\delta <\varepsilon _{\beta }$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] Since the epsilon numbers are an unbounded subclass of the ordinal numbers, they are enumerated using the ordinal numbers themselves.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] For any ordinal number $\beta$ , $\varepsilon _{\beta }$ is the least epsilon number (fixed point of the exponential map) not already in the set $\{\varepsilon _{\delta }\mid \delta <\beta \}$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] Any epsilon number ε has Cantor normal form $\varepsilon =\omega ^{\varepsilon }$ , which means that the Cantor normal form is not very useful for epsilon numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] The ordinals less than *ε*0, however, can be usefully described by their Cantor normal forms, which leads to a representation of *ε*0 as the ordered set of all finite rooted trees, as follows.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] Each of the ordinals $\beta _{1},\ldots ,\beta _{k}$ in turn has a similar Cantor normal form.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] We obtain the finite rooted tree representing α by joining the roots of the trees representing $\beta _{1},\ldots ,\beta _{k}$ to a new root.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] In this way the set of all finite rooted trees becomes a well-ordered set which is order isomorphic to *ε*0.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] This representation is related to the proof of the hydra theorem, which represents decreasing sequences of ordinals as a graph-theoretic game.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] The fixed points of the "epsilon mapping" $x\mapsto \varepsilon _{x}$ form a normal function, whose fixed points form a normal function; this is known as the Veblen hierarchy (the Veblen functions with base *φ*0(*α*) = *ω**α*).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] Continuing in this vein, one can define maps *φ**α* for progressively larger ordinals α (including, by this rarefied form of transfinite recursion, limit ordinals), with progressively larger least fixed points *φ**α*+1(0).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] The least ordinal not reachable from 0 by this procedure—i. e., the least ordinal α for which *φ**α*(0) = *α*, or equivalently the first fixed point of the map $\alpha \mapsto \varphi _{\alpha }(0)$ —is the Feferman–Schütte ordinal Γ0.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] In *On Numbers and Games*, the classic exposition on surreal numbers, John Horton Conway provided a number of examples of concepts that had natural extensions from the ordinals to the surreals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] One such function is the $\omega$ -map $n\mapsto \omega ^{n}$ ; this mapping generalises naturally to include all surreal numbers in its domain, which in turn provides a natural generalisation of the Cantor normal form for surreal numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] It is natural to consider any fixed point of this expanded map to be an epsilon number, whether or not it happens to be strictly an ordinal number.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] There is a natural way to define $\varepsilon _{n}$ for every surreal number *n*, and the map remains order-preserving.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/epsilon-number] Conway goes on to define a broader class of "irreducible" surreal numbers that includes the epsilon numbers as a particularly interesting subclass.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In set theory, an **ordinal number**, or **ordinal**, is a generalization of ordinal numerals (first, second, nth, etc.) aimed to extend enumeration to infinite sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Usually Greek letters are used for ordinal number variables to help distinguish them from natural number variables.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A finite set can be enumerated by successively labeling each element with the least natural number that has not been previously used.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This more general definition allows us to define an ordinal number $\omega$ (omega) to be the least element that is greater than every natural number, along with ordinal numbers ⁠ $\omega +1$ ⁠, ⁠ $\omega +2$ ⁠, etc., which are even greater than ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory asserts that, for *any* set of ordinals, there exists another ordinal greater than all of them.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The answer to the question "What if that set is the set of all ordinals?" (the Burali-Forti paradox) is that the collection of all ordinals is not a set, but a proper class.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A linear order such that every non-empty subset has a least element is called a well-order.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The axiom of choice implies that every set can be well-ordered.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Given two well-ordered sets, one is isomorphic to an initial segment of the other, and the isomorphism is unique.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This allows a unique ordinal to be associated with each well-ordered set, known as its order type.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Ordinal numbers are distinct from cardinal numbers, which measure the size of sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Although the distinction between ordinals and cardinals is not this apparent on finite sets (one can go from one to the other just by counting labels), they are very different in the infinite case, where different infinite ordinals can correspond to sets having the same cardinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Like other kinds of numbers, ordinals can be added, multiplied, and exponentiated, although none of these operations are commutative.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Ordinals were introduced by Georg Cantor in 1883 to accommodate infinite sequences and classify derived sets, which he had previously introduced in 1872 while studying the uniqueness of trigonometric series.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A natural number (which, in this context, includes the number 0) can be used for two purposes: to describe the *size* of a set, or to describe the *position* of an element in a sequence.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] When generalized to infinite sets, the notion of size leads to cardinal numbers, and the notion of position leads to the ordinal numbers described here.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In a broader mathematical sense, counting can be viewed as the instantiation of mathematical induction.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] To enumerate a well-ordered set is effectively to verify a property for its elements sequentially.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] For the natural numbers, this is standard induction: if a property holds for 0, and its truth for ⁠ n ⁠ implies its truth for ⁠ $n+1$ ⁠, then it holds for all natural numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This process corresponds to the first infinite ordinal, ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Mathematical contexts often require iterating beyond a single infinite limit.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The ordinal ⁠ $\omega ^{2}$ ⁠ (represented in the figure) exemplifies the concept of **nested induction**.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] It consists of a sequence of distinct copies of the natural numbers ordered one after another.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] To verify a property for all ordinals less than ⁠ $\omega ^{2}$ ⁠, one performs an "inner" induction (counting through ⁠ $0,1,2,\dots$ ⁠), establishes the limit at ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, and then proceeds to the next sequence (⁠ $\omega +1,\omega +2,\dots$ ⁠).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This structure parallels a nested loop in computer programming (e.g., iterating through pairs of natural numbers ⁠ $(j,i)$ ⁠ ordered lexicographically).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Ordinals allow the definition of processes of arbitrary complexity, such as ⁠ $\omega ^{3}$ ⁠ (triple nesting) or ⁠ $\omega ^{\omega }$ ⁠ (induction over the depth of nested induction).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The validity of inductive counting rests on the property of well-foundedness, specifically the requirement that every process can be traced back to a "foundational" element.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A linear order that exhibits this well-foundedness is termed a well-order.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The existence of a "least" or minimal element in every non-empty subset of a well-ordered set grounds the principle of transfinite induction, generalizing standard induction by ensuring that if a property fails to hold, there exists a specific least counterexample.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Ordinals serve as the canonical abstractions of these well-ordered structures.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A fundamental theorem in set theory establishes that any two well-ordered sets are comparable: given two well-orders, either they are isomorphic, or one is isomorphic to a proper initial segment of the other.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This uniqueness implies that well-orders can be classified by their structure alone, independent of specific representations.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Consequently, **ordinal numbers** are defined as the representative forms of these isomorphism classes.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The construction procedure of transfinite sequences implies that the ordinals used to label their elements are well-ordered.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Intuitively, the least ordinal in ⁠ T ⁠ is the "next" ordinal introduced after all ordinals strictly less than every ordinal in ⁠ T ⁠ have been used.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In contrast, ⁠ T ⁠ need not have a greatest element, for example when ⁠ T ⁠ is the set of all natural numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Being well-ordered is stronger than merely being linearly ordered.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] For example, the real numbers are naturally linearly ordered, but any open interval has no least element.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The importance of well-ordering is that it enables transfinite induction.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] If a statement ⁠ $P(\alpha )$ ⁠ about an ordinal ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠ is not universally true for all ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠, i.e., if it has any counterexamples, then it must have a least counterexample.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Conversely, if it can be proven that ⁠ $P(\alpha )$ ⁠ is true whenever ⁠ $P(\beta )$ ⁠ is true for all ⁠ $\beta <\alpha$ ⁠, then it cannot have any least counterexample, and thus it cannot have any counterexample at all, i.e., it is indeed universally true.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In the usual Zermelo–Fraenkel (ZF) formalization of set theory, a well-ordered set is a totally ordered set ⁠ $(S,\leq )$ ⁠ such that every non-empty subset ⁠ $T\subseteq S$ ⁠ has a least element.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Here “set” means a collection that is itself an object of ZF, as opposed to a proper class.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A well-ordered set can be written as a transfinite sequence by assigning ordinal labels to its elements in a way that respects ordering: ⁠ $a_{\alpha }\leq a_{\beta }$ ⁠ if and only if ⁠ $\alpha \leq \beta$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] (Such a one-to-one correspondence between two ordered sets is called an order isomorphism.) The labels used in such an enumeration form an initial segment of the ordinals, in the sense that if a label is used then every smaller ordinal label is also used.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] By well-orderedness, there is a unique least ordinal that is not used as a label; this ordinal determines the "length" of the sequence, and is called the order type of the well-ordering.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Thanks to 0-based indexing, the order type coincides with the cardinality for finite sets, including the empty set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] However, for infinite sets, different well-order relations ⁠ $\leq$ ⁠ can have different order types.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Order types can be defined without a preexisting notion of ordinals, by working directly with order isomorphisms between general well-ordered sets, just as cardinality can be defined through bijections between general (unordered) sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] As with bijections, being order-isomorphic is an equivalence relation on well-ordered sets; its equivalence classes correspond to order types (ordinals).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In the *Principia Mathematica* approach, the order type of a well-ordered set ⁠ $(S,\leq )$ ⁠ is *identified with* its isomorphism class, i.e., the set of all well-ordered sets ⁠ $(S',\leq ')$ ⁠ order-isomorphic to ⁠ $(S,\leq )$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Since elements of ⁠ $S'$ ⁠ are allowed to be *anything*, this definition has the “set of all sets” flavor, and in ZF such collections are generally too large to be sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This definition can still be used in type theory and in Quine's axiomatic set theory New Foundations and related systems.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In ZF and related systems of axiomatic set theory, these equivalence classes are generally too large to form sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Consequently, it is necessary to select a unique, canonical representative from each class—a single set that embodies the structure of the well-ordering.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Since the fundamental relation in set theory is set membership (⁠ $\in$ ⁠), the ideal representation is one where the abstract order relation ⁠ < ⁠ is translated directly into the membership relation ⁠ $\in$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The **von Neumann representation** provides this canonical form.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] It relies on the observation that any well-founded relation satisfying certain properties can be mapped to a specific set where the relation becomes set membership.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This mapping is known as the Mostowski collapse lemma.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] When applied to a well-ordering, the Mostowski collapse yields a specific set ⁠ S ⁠ where the order relation ⁠ $x<y$ ⁠ is true if and only if ⁠ $x\in y$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The resulting sets have the property that they are transitive: every element of ⁠ S ⁠ is also a subset of ⁠ S ⁠ (i.e., the union of the set is contained within the set).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In this representation, each ordinal is identified with the set of all preceding ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The first infinite ordinal ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠ is represented by the set of all finite ordinals, i.e., the set of von Neumann natural numbers ⁠ $\mathbb {N} =\{0,1,2,\ldots \}$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Informally, one may define an ordinal recursively as a downward closed set of ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Such a recursive definition is usually justified with the transitive closure.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The set ⁠ $\omega \equiv \mathbb {N}$ ⁠ is usually defined as the smallest inductive set (containing ⁠ $\emptyset$ ⁠ and closed under successor).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The "smallest" constraint guarantees that each element of ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠ is either zero or the successor of another element of ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, which allows induction to demonstrate that ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠ indeed satisfies the formal definition of ordinals stated above.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The non-strict order relation ⁠ $\leq$ ⁠ has an alternative characterization: ⁠ $\alpha \leq \beta$ ⁠ if and only if ⁠ $\alpha \subseteq \beta$ ⁠ for ordinals ⁠ $\alpha ,\beta$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This implies that ⁠ $\leq$ ⁠ is a partial order.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] So all ordinal numbers form a well-ordered class ⁠ $\mathrm {ON}$ ⁠, and thus any nonempty set of ordinals equipped with ⁠ $\leq$ ⁠ is a well-ordered set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The explicit forms of ⁠ $\mathrm {succ}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\sup$ ⁠ imply that for any set of ordinals, there exists another ordinal greater than all of them.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Every well-ordered set S is order-isomorphic to exactly one ordinal, known as its *order type*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Uniqueness is guaranteed because a well-ordered set cannot be isomorphic to a proper initial segment of itself, preventing isomorphism to two distinct ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The existence of this ordinal is proven by defining a map pairing each $x\in S$ with the ordinal representing the order type of the initial segment ⁠ $S_{x}=\{y\in S\mid y<x\}$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] By the Axiom schema of replacement, the range of this map is a set of ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Because this range is downward closed (the order type of a segment of a segment is a smaller ordinal), the range is itself an ordinal $\gamma$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The domain of the isomorphism must be all of S ; otherwise, the least element $z\in S$ outside the domain would imply $S_{z}\cong \gamma$ , which would effectively include z in the domain, a contradiction.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Every ordinal number is one of three types: the ordinal zero, a successor ordinal, or a limit ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] There is variation in the definition of limit ordinals regarding the inclusion of zero.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Some texts, such as *Introduction to Cardinal Arithmetic* by Holz et al., define a limit ordinal as a non-zero ordinal that is not a successor.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In contrast, other standard set theory texts, including Jech's *Set Theory* and Just and Weese's *Discovering Modern Set Theory*, define a limit ordinal simply as any ordinal that is not a successor, which implies that 0 is a limit ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] When the topological definition is used (based on the order topology), 0 is not a limit ordinal because it is not a limit point of the set of smaller ordinals (which is empty); Rosenstein's *Linear Orderings* uses this definition.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] When 0 is included as a limit, ordinals that are strictly greater than 0 and not successors are usually referred to as "nonzero limit ordinals".
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] For example, $\omega$ is a limit ordinal because any natural number is less than ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, and the successor of any natural number is also a natural number (hence less than ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] It is the least limit ordinal because each natural number ⁠ $n\in \omega$ ⁠ is either zero or a successor.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Any strictly decreasing sequence of ordinals ⁠ $\alpha _{0}>\alpha _{1}>\alpha _{2}>\cdots$ ⁠ must be finite.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This follows directly from the natural ordering of ordinals being a well-order: if there existed such an infinite decreasing sequence, then the set ⁠ $\{\alpha _{i}\mid i\in \mathbb {N} \}$ ⁠ would be a set of ordinals without a least element.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] By the same argument, a well-ordered set has no infinite strictly descending chains; in fact, assuming the axiom of dependent choice, any total order that satisfies this condition is a well-order, giving an alternative characterization of well-ordered sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This property may be surprising when the initial value is an infinite ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Indeed, for sequences starting from a natural number ⁠ n ⁠, the longest sequence is always one that decreases by 1 every step, leading to a sequence with ⁠ n ⁠ steps (⁠ $n+1$ ⁠ elements).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This strategy of descending to the immediate predecessor remains valid for successor ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] However, a limit ordinal ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ has no immediate predecessor to descend to, so any next term must jump to some ⁠ $\beta <\lambda$ ⁠, skipping infinitely many ordinals strictly between ⁠ $\beta$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] For example, when descending from ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, one must choose a finite natural number, and thus "commit" to the number of maximum remaining steps.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Descending from ⁠ $\omega \cdot k$ ⁠ allows one to make such a commitment ⁠ k ⁠ times, and descending from ⁠ $\omega ^{2}$ ⁠ allows one to commit to a finite value of ⁠ k ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Larger ordinals may allow more complicated decision structures, but the number of descending steps remains unbounded but finite.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This property is useful for proving termination for any procedure.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] If the states of a computation (computer program or game) can be well-ordered—in such a way that each step is followed by a "lower" step—then the computation will terminate.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] If $\alpha$ is any ordinal and X is a set, an $\alpha$ -indexed sequence of elements of X is a function from $\alpha$ to X .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This concept, a **transfinite sequence** (if $\alpha$ is infinite) or *ordinal-indexed sequence*, is a generalization of the concept of a sequence.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] An ordinary sequence corresponds to the case $\alpha =\omega$ , while a finite $\alpha$ corresponds to a tuple, a.k.a. string.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] While a sequence indexed by a specific ordinal $\alpha$ is a set, a sequence indexed by the class of all ordinals is a proper class.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The Axiom schema of replacement guarantees that any initial segment of such a class-sequence (the restriction of the function to some specific ordinal $\delta$ ) is a set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A sequence is called **normal** if it is both strictly increasing and continuous.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] If a sequence *f* is increasing (not necessarily strictly) and continuous and λ is a limit ordinal, then $f(\lambda )=\bigcup _{\beta <\lambda }f(\beta )$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Transfinite induction holds in any well-ordered set, but it is so important in relation to ordinals that it is worth restating here.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Any property that passes from the set of ordinals smaller than a given ordinal α to α itself, is true of all ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] That is, if *P*(α) is true whenever *P*(β) is true for all β < α, then *P*(α) is true for *all* α.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Or, more practically: in order to prove a property *P* for all ordinals α, one can assume that it is already known for all smaller β < α.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Transfinite induction can be used not only to prove theorems but also to define functions on ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This is known as *transfinite recursion*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Formally, a function F is defined by transfinite recursion on the ordinals if, for every ordinal α, the value ⁠ $F(\alpha )$ ⁠ is specified using the set of values $\{F(\beta )\mid \beta <\alpha \}$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] *Successor step*: Define $F(\alpha +1)$ assuming $F(\alpha )$ is defined.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] *Limit step*: For a limit ordinal $\lambda$ , define $F(\lambda )$ as the limit of $F(\beta )$ for all $\beta <\lambda$ (either in the sense of ordinal limits or some other notion of limit if the codomain allows it).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The interesting step in the definition is usually the successor step.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] If $F(\alpha )$ for limit ordinals $\alpha$ is defined as the limsup of $F(\beta )$ for $\beta <\alpha$ and F takes ordinal values and is non-decreasing, the function F will be continuous as defined above.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Ordinal addition, multiplication and exponentiation are continuous as functions of their second argument.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The existence and uniqueness of such a function are proven by constructing it as the union of partial approximations.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] *Uniqueness and Compatibility:* One proves that any two recursion segments agree on their common domain.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] *Global Definition:* The global class function F is defined as the union of all such unique recursion segments.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] For any ordinal α, the value ⁠ $F(\alpha )$ ⁠ is the value assigned to α by any recursion segment defined on a domain larger than α.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The rigorous justification for local existence relies on the axiom schema of replacement for the step of limit ordinals in order to collect the recursion segments into a set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This construction allows definitions such as ordinal addition, multiplication, and exponentiation to be rigorous.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The principle of transfinite recursion also implies that recursion can be performed up to a specific ordinal $\delta$ (defining a set rather than a proper class).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This is often used to define sequences of length $\omega$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] For example, to prove that a normal function f has arbitrarily large fixed points, one constructs a sequence starting with any ordinal $\gamma _{0}$ and defines $\gamma _{n+1}=f(\gamma _{n})$ by recursion on $n<\omega$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Then the limit $\delta =\sup _{n<\omega }\gamma _{n}$ is a fixed point of f because continuity ensures $f(\delta )=f(\sup \gamma _{n})=\sup f(\gamma _{n})=\sup \gamma _{n+1}=\delta$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Any well-ordered set is similar (order-isomorphic) to a unique ordinal number $\alpha$ ; in other words, its elements can be indexed in increasing fashion by the ordinals less than ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This applies, in particular, to any set of ordinals: any set of ordinals is naturally indexed by the ordinals less than some ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] So the $\gamma$ -th element in the class (with the convention that the "0-th" is the smallest, the "1-st" is the next smallest, and so on) can be freely spoken of.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Formally, the definition is by transfinite induction: the $\gamma$ -th element of the class is defined (provided it has already been defined for all $\beta <\gamma$ ), as the smallest element greater than the $\beta$ -th element for all ⁠ $\beta <\gamma$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This could be applied, for example, to the class of limit ordinals: the $\gamma$ -th ordinal, which is either a limit or zero is $\omega \cdot \gamma$ (see ordinal arithmetic for the definition of multiplication of ordinals).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Similarly, one can consider *additively indecomposable ordinals* (meaning a nonzero ordinal that is not the sum of two strictly smaller ordinals): the $\gamma$ -th additively indecomposable ordinal is indexed as ⁠ $\omega ^{\gamma }$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The technique of indexing classes of ordinals is often useful in the context of fixed points: for example, the $\gamma$ -th ordinal $\alpha$ such that $\omega ^{\alpha }=\alpha$ is written ⁠ $\varepsilon _{\gamma }$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] There are three usual operations on ordinals: addition, multiplication, and exponentiation.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Each can be defined in essentially two different ways: either by constructing an explicit well-ordered set that represents the operation or by using transfinite recursion.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The Cantor normal form provides a standardized way of writing ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] It uniquely represents each ordinal as a finite sum of ordinal powers of ω.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] However, this cannot form the basis of a universal ordinal notation due to such self-referential representations as ε0 = ωε0.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Ordinals are a subclass of the class of surreal numbers, and the so-called "natural" arithmetical operations for surreal numbers are an alternative way to combine ordinals arithmetically.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] They retain commutativity at the expense of continuity.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Interpreted as *nimbers*, a game-theoretic variant of numbers, ordinals can also be combined via nimber arithmetic operations.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] These operations are commutative but the restriction to natural numbers is generally not the same as ordinary addition of natural numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Each ordinal associates with one cardinal, its cardinality.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] If there is a bijection between two ordinals (e.g. ω = 1 + ω and ω + 1 > ω), then they associate with the same cardinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Any well-ordered set having an ordinal as its order-type has the same cardinality as that ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The least ordinal associated with a given cardinal is called the *initial ordinal* of that cardinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Every finite ordinal (natural number) is initial, and no other ordinal associates with its cardinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] But most infinite ordinals are not initial, as many infinite ordinals associate with the same cardinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The axiom of choice is equivalent to the statement that every set can be well-ordered, i.e. that every cardinal has an initial ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In theories with the axiom of choice, the cardinal number of any set has an initial ordinal, and one may employ the Von Neumann cardinal assignment as the cardinal's representation.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] (However, we must then be careful to distinguish between cardinal arithmetic and ordinal arithmetic.) In set theories without the axiom of choice, a cardinal may be represented by the set of sets with that cardinality having minimal rank (see Scott's trick).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] One issue with Scott's trick is that it identifies the cardinal number 0 with ⁠ $\{\emptyset \}$ ⁠, which in some formulations is the ordinal number ⁠ 1 ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] It may be clearer to apply Von Neumann cardinal assignment to finite cases and to use Scott's trick for sets which are infinite or do not admit well orderings.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Note that cardinal and ordinal arithmetic agree for finite numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The α-th infinite initial ordinal is written ⁠ $\omega _{\alpha }$ ⁠, it is always a limit ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Its cardinality is written ⁠ $\aleph _{\alpha }$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] For example, the cardinality of ω0 = ω is ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠, which is also the cardinality of ω2 or ε0 (all are countable ordinals).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] So ω can be identified with ⁠ $\aleph _{0}$ ⁠, except that the notation $\aleph _{0}$ is used when writing cardinals, and ω when writing ordinals (this is important since, for example, $\aleph _{0}^{2}$ = $\aleph _{0}$ whereas $\omega ^{2}>\omega$ ).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The cofinality of an ordinal $\alpha$ is the smallest ordinal $\delta$ that is the order type of a cofinal subset of ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Notice that a number of authors define cofinality or use it only for limit ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The cofinality of a set of ordinals or any other well-ordered set is the cofinality of the order type of that set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Thus for a limit ordinal, there exists a $\delta$ -indexed strictly increasing sequence with limit ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] For example, the cofinality of ω2 is ω, because the sequence ω·*m* (where *m* ranges over the natural numbers) tends to ω2; but, more generally, any countable limit ordinal has cofinality ω.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] An uncountable limit ordinal may have either cofinality ω as does $\omega _{\omega }$ or an uncountable cofinality.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] And the cofinality of any successor ordinal is 1.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The cofinality of any limit ordinal is at least ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] An ordinal that is equal to its cofinality is called regular and it is always an initial ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Any limit of regular ordinals is a limit of initial ordinals and thus is also initial even if it is not regular, which it usually is not.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] If the axiom of choice holds, then $\omega _{\alpha +1}$ is regular for each *α*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In this case, the ordinals 0, 1, ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, ⁠ $\omega _{1}$ ⁠, and $\omega _{2}$ are regular, whereas 2, 3, ⁠ $\omega _{\omega }$ ⁠, and ωω·2 are initial ordinals that are not regular.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The cofinality of any ordinal *α* is a regular ordinal, i.e. the cofinality of the cofinality of *α* is the same as the cofinality of *α*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] So the cofinality operation is idempotent.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The concepts of closed and unbounded sets are typically formulated for subsets of a regular cardinal $\kappa$ that is uncountable.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A subset $C\subseteq \kappa$ is said to be *unbounded* (or cofinal) in $\kappa$ if for every ordinal $\alpha <\kappa$ , there exists some $\beta \in C$ such that $\alpha <\beta$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] To define the property of being closed, one first defines a limit point: a non-zero ordinal $\delta <\kappa$ is a limit point of C if $\sup(C\cap \delta )=\delta$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The set C is *closed* in $\kappa$ if it contains all of its limit points below $\kappa$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A set that is both closed and unbounded is commonly referred to as a *club set*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Examples of club sets are fundamental to set theory.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The set of all limit ordinals less than $\kappa$ is a club set, as there is always a limit ordinal greater than any given ordinal below $\kappa$ , and a limit of limit ordinals is itself a limit ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] If $\kappa$ is a limit cardinal, the set of all cardinals below $\kappa$ is unbounded, and its set of limit points—the limit cardinals—forms a closed unbounded set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Furthermore, if $\kappa$ is a strong limit cardinal (such as an inaccessible cardinal), the set of strong limit cardinals below $\kappa$ is also a club set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Another significant example arises from normal functions (functions $f:\kappa \to \kappa$ that are strictly increasing and continuous); the range of any normal function is a closed unbounded subset of $\kappa$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Club sets possess structural properties that allow them to generate a filter.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Because $\kappa$ is regular and uncountable, the intersection of any two club sets is also a club set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] More generally, the intersection of fewer than $\kappa$ club sets is a club set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Consequently, the collection of all subsets of $\kappa$ that contain a club set forms a $\kappa$ -complete non-principal filter, known as the *closed unbounded filter* (or club filter).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A subset $S\subseteq \kappa$ is termed *stationary* if it has a non-empty intersection with every closed unbounded set in $\kappa$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Intuitively, stationary sets are "large" enough that they cannot be avoided by any club set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Using the notation of filters, a set is stationary if and only if it does not belong to the dual ideal of the club filter (the ideal of non-stationary sets).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] While every club set is stationary, not every stationary set is a club; for instance, a stationary set S may fail to be closed.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Furthermore, while the intersection of a stationary set and a club set is stationary, the intersection of two stationary sets may be empty.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The distinction between club sets and stationary sets is central to the definitions of certain large cardinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] If $\kappa$ is the smallest inaccessible cardinal, the set of singular strong limit cardinals below $\kappa$ forms a closed unbounded set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Because this club set contains no regular cardinals, the set of regular cardinals below the first inaccessible is not stationary.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This remains true if $\kappa$ is the n -th inaccessible cardinal for some $n<\kappa$ ; the regular cardinals below it will not form a stationary set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A cardinal $\kappa$ is defined as a Mahlo cardinal precisely when the set of regular cardinals below it is stationary.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] By relaxing the condition on the limit cardinals, one defines a cardinal as *weakly Mahlo* if it is weakly inaccessible and the set of regular cardinals below it is stationary.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The closed unbounded filter is not an ultrafilter under the standard Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory with the Axiom of Choice (ZFC).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This is because one can find two disjoint stationary sets, which precludes the filter from deciding membership for every subset.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] For any regular cardinal $\kappa >\omega _{1}$ , the set of ordinals with cofinality $\omega$ and the set of ordinals with cofinality $\omega _{1}$ are disjoint stationary subsets of $\kappa$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In the specific case of $\kappa =\omega _{1}$ , the non-existence of an ultrafilter relies on the Axiom of Choice.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Under ZFC, the set of limit ordinals in $\omega _{1}$ can be partitioned into $\omega _{1}$ disjoint stationary sets (a result related to Fodor's lemma).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] However, in models of set theory without the Axiom of Choice, such as those satisfying the Axiom of determinacy, the club filter on $\omega _{1}$ can be an ultrafilter, a property connected to $\omega _{1}$ being a measurable cardinal in those contexts.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] These definitions generalize to proper classes of ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A class C of ordinals is unbounded if it contains arbitrarily large ordinals, and closed if the limit of any sequence of ordinals in C is also in C .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This topological definition is equivalent to assuming the indexing class-function of C is continuous.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Notable examples of closed unbounded classes include the class of all infinite cardinals, the class of limit cardinals, and the class of fixed points of the $\aleph$ -function.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In contrast, the class of regular cardinals is unbounded but not closed.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] A class is stationary if it intersects every closed unbounded class.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] As mentioned above (see Cantor normal form), the ordinal ε0 is the smallest satisfying the equation ⁠ $\omega ^{\alpha }=\alpha$ ⁠, so it is the limit of the sequence 0, 1, ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, ⁠ $\omega ^{\omega }$ ⁠, ⁠ $\omega ^{\omega ^{\omega }}$ ⁠, etc.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] One could try to do this systematically, but no matter what system is used to define and construct ordinals, there is always an ordinal that lies just above all the ordinals constructed by the system.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Considerably large ordinals can be defined below ⁠ $\omega _{1}^{\mathrm {CK} }$ ⁠, however, which measure the proof-theoretic strength of certain formal systems (for example, $\varepsilon _{0}$ measures the strength of Peano arithmetic).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Large countable ordinals such as countable admissible ordinals can also be defined above the Church-Kleene ordinal, which are of interest in various parts of logic.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Any ordinal number can be made into a topological space by endowing it with the order topology.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] This topology is discrete if and only if it is less than or equal to ω.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In contrast, a subset of ω + 1 is open in the order topology if and only if either it is cofinite or it does not contain ω as an element.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] See the Topology and ordinals section of the "Order topology" article.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The transfinite ordinal numbers, which first appeared in 1883, originated in Cantor's work with derived sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] If *P* is a set of real numbers, the derived set *P′* is the set of limit points of *P*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In 1872, Cantor generated the sets *P*(*n*) by applying the derived set operation *n* times to *P*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In 1880, he pointed out that these sets form the sequence *P'*⊇ ··· ⊇ *P*(*n*) ⊇ *P*(*n* + 1) ⊇ ···, and he continued the derivation process by defining *P*(∞) as the intersection of these sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Then he iterated the derived set operation and intersections to extend his sequence of sets into the infinite: *P*(∞) ⊇ *P*(∞ + 1) ⊇ *P*(∞ + 2) ⊇ ··· ⊇ *P*(2∞) ⊇ ··· ⊇ *P*(∞2) ⊇ ···.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The superscripts containing ∞ are just indices defined by the derivation process.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Conversely, if *P′* is countable, then there is an index *α* such that *P*(*α*) = ∅.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Hence, they are discrete sets, so they are countable.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Proof of first theorem: If *P*(*α*) = ∅ for some index *α*, then *P′* is the countable union of countable sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The second theorem requires proving the existence of an *α* such that *P*(*α*) = ∅.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] To prove this, Cantor considered the set of all *α* having countably many predecessors.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] To define this set, he defined the transfinite ordinal numbers and transformed the infinite indices into ordinals by replacing ∞ with *ω*, the first transfinite ordinal number.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Cantor called the set of finite ordinals the first **number class**.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The second number class is the set of ordinals whose predecessors form a countably infinite set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The set of all *α* having countably many predecessors—that is, the set of countable ordinals—is the union of these two number classes.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Cantor proved that the cardinality of the second number class is the first uncountable cardinality.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Cantor's second theorem becomes: If *P′* is countable, then there is a countable ordinal *α* such that *P*(*α*) = ∅.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Let *P′* be countable, and assume there is no such α.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] In both cases, *P′* is uncountable, which contradicts *P′* being countable.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Therefore, there is a countable ordinal *α* such that *P*(*α*) = ∅.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Cantor's work with derived sets and ordinal numbers led to the Cantor-Bendixson theorem.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Using successors, limits, and cardinality, Cantor generated an unbounded sequence of ordinal numbers and number classes.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The (*α* + 1)-th number class is the set of ordinals whose predecessors form a set of the same cardinality as the *α*-th number class.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] The cardinality of the (*α* + 1)-th number class is the cardinality immediately following that of the *α*-th number class.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] For a limit ordinal *α*, the *α*-th number class is the union of the *β*-th number classes for *β* < *α*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Its cardinality is the limit of the cardinalities of these number classes.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] If *n* is finite, the *n*-th number class has cardinality ⁠ $\aleph _{n-1}$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] If *α* ≥ *ω*, the *α*-th number class has cardinality ⁠ $\aleph _{\alpha }$ ⁠.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Therefore, the cardinalities of the number classes correspond one-to-one with the aleph numbers.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Also, the *α*-th number class consists of ordinals different from those in the preceding number classes if and only if *α* is a non-limit ordinal.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/ordinal-number] Therefore, the non-limit number classes partition the ordinals into pairwise disjoint sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] Such an ⁠ $\alpha$ ⁠ is just a minimal counterexample, the existence of which is guaranteed by the fact the class of ordinal numbers is well-ordered.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] All three cases are identical except for the type of ordinal considered.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] They do not formally need to be considered separately, but in practice the proofs are typically so different as to require separate presentations.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] Zero is sometimes considered a limit ordinal and then may sometimes be treated in proofs in the same case as limit ordinals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] As an example, a basis for a (possibly infinite-dimensional) vector space can be created by starting with the empty set and for each ordinal *α > 0* choosing a vector that is not in the span of the vectors $\{v_{\beta }\mid \beta <\alpha \}$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] This process stops when no vector can be chosen.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] Note that we require the domains of *G*2, *G*3 to be broad enough to make the above properties meaningful.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] The uniqueness of the sequence satisfying these properties can be proved using transfinite induction.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] More generally, one can define objects by transfinite recursion on any well-founded relation *R*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] Proofs or constructions using induction and recursion often use the axiom of choice to produce a well-ordered relation that can be treated by transfinite induction.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] However, if the relation in question is already well-ordered, one can often use transfinite induction without invoking the axiom of choice.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] For example, many results about Borel sets are proved by transfinite induction on the ordinal rank of the set; these ranks are already well-ordered, so the axiom of choice is not needed to well-order them.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] The above argument uses the axiom of choice in an essential way at the very beginning, in order to well-order the reals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] After that step, the axiom of choice is not used again.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] Other uses of the axiom of choice are more subtle.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] For example, a construction by transfinite recursion frequently will not specify a *unique* value for *A**α*+1, given the sequence up to *α*, but will specify only a *condition* that *A**α*+1 must satisfy, and argue that there is at least one set satisfying this condition.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] If it is not possible to define a unique example of such a set at each stage, then it may be necessary to invoke (some form of) the axiom of choice to select one such at each step.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] For inductions and recursions of countable length, the weaker axiom of dependent choice is sufficient.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/transfinite-induction] Because there are models of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory of interest to set theorists that satisfy the axiom of dependent choice but not the full axiom of choice, the knowledge that a particular proof only requires dependent choice can be useful.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] In mathematics, a **well-order** (or **well-ordering** or **well-order relation**) on a set S is a total ordering on S with the property that every non-empty subset of S has a least element in this ordering.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] The set S together with the ordering is then called a **well-ordered set** (or **woset**).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] In some academic articles and textbooks these terms are instead written as **wellorder**, **wellordered**, and **wellordering** or **well order**, **well ordered**, and **well ordering**.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Every non-empty well-ordered set has a least element.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Every element s of a well-ordered set, except a possible greatest element, has a unique successor (next element), namely the least element of the subset of all elements greater than s.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] There may be elements, besides the least element, that have no predecessor (see § Natural numbers below for an example).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] A well-ordered set S contains for every subset T with an upper bound a least upper bound, namely the least element of the subset of all upper bounds of T in S.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] If ≤ is a non-strict well ordering, then < is a strict well ordering.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] A relation is a strict well ordering if and only if it is a well-founded strict total order.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] The distinction between strict and non-strict well orders is often ignored since they are easily interconvertible.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Every well-ordered set is uniquely order isomorphic to a unique ordinal number, called the order type of the well-ordered set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] The well-ordering theorem, which is equivalent to the axiom of choice, states that every set can be well ordered.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] If a set is well ordered (or even if it merely admits a well-founded relation), the proof technique of transfinite induction can be used to prove that a given statement is true for all elements of the set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] The observation that the natural numbers are well ordered by the usual less-than relation is commonly called the well-ordering principle (for natural numbers).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] The standard ordering ≤ of the natural numbers is a well ordering and has the additional property that every non-zero natural number has a unique predecessor.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] This is a well-ordered set of order type *ω* + *ω*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Every element has a successor (there is no largest element).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Two elements lack a predecessor: 0 and 1.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Unlike the standard ordering ≤ of the natural numbers, the standard ordering ≤ of the integers is not a well ordering, since, for example, the set of negative integers does not contain a least element.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] R is isomorphic to the ordinal number *ω* + *ω*.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] The standard ordering ≤ of any real interval is not a well ordering, since, for example, the open interval ⁠ $(0,1)\subseteq [0,1]$ ⁠ does not contain a least element.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] From the ZFC axioms of set theory (including the axiom of choice) one can show that there is a well order of the reals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Also Wacław Sierpiński proved that ZF + GCH (the generalized continuum hypothesis) imply the axiom of choice and hence a well order of the reals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Nonetheless, it is possible to show that the ZFC+GCH axioms alone are not sufficient to prove the existence of a definable (by a formula) well order of the reals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] However it is consistent with ZFC that a definable well ordering of the reals exists—for example, it is consistent with ZFC that V=L, and it follows from ZFC+V=L that a particular formula well orders the reals, or indeed any set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] An uncountable subset of the real numbers with the standard ordering ≤ cannot be a well order: Suppose X is a subset of ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ well ordered by ≤.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] For each x in X, let *s*(*x*) be the successor of x in ≤ ordering on X (unless x is the last element of X).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Let $A=\{(x,s(x))\,|\,x\in X\}$ whose elements are nonempty and disjoint intervals.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Each such interval contains at least one rational number, so there is an injective function from A to ⁠ $\mathbb {Q} .$ ⁠ There is an injection from X to A (except possibly for a last element of X, which could be mapped to zero later).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] And it is well known that there is an injection from ⁠ $\mathbb {Q}$ ⁠ to the natural numbers (which could be chosen to avoid hitting zero).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Thus there is an injection from X to the natural numbers, which means that X is countable.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] On the other hand, a countably infinite subset of the reals may or may not be a well order with the standard ≤.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Transfinite induction works for the entire ordered set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Every strictly decreasing sequence of elements of the set must terminate after only finitely many steps (assuming the axiom of dependent choice).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Every subordering is isomorphic to an initial segment (see § initial segments below).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] An **initial segment**, determined by an element x of a poset X , is a subset of form $\{y\in X\mid y<x\}$ .
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] By convention, X itself is also counted as an (improper) initial segment.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] In other words, an initial segment is the same thing as a lower set in order theory and this characterization is sometimes also taken as a definition of an initial segment.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Initial segments are often used in the study of well-ordered sets and well-founded sets.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Initial segments are also used in the statement of the transfinite recursion theorem.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Every well-ordered set can be made into a topological space by endowing it with the order topology.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] A subset is cofinal in the whole set if and only if it is unbounded in the whole set or it has a maximum that is also maximum of the whole set.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] A well-ordered set as topological space is a first-countable space if and only if it has order type less than or equal to ω1 (omega-one), that is, if and only if the set is countable or has the smallest uncountable order type.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] The position of each element within the ordered set is also given by an ordinal number.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] In the case of a finite set, the basic operation of counting, to find the ordinal number of a particular object, or to find the object with a particular ordinal number, corresponds to assigning ordinal numbers one by one to the objects.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] The size (number of elements, cardinal number) of a finite set is equal to the order type.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Counting in the everyday sense typically starts from one, so it assigns to each object the size of the initial segment with that object as last element.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Note that these numbers are one more than the formal ordinal numbers according to the isomorphic order, because these are equal to the number of earlier objects (which corresponds to counting from zero).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] Thus for finite n, the expression "n-th element" of a well-ordered set requires context to know whether this counts from zero or one.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] In an expression "β-th element" where β can also be an infinite ordinal, it will typically count from zero.
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] For an infinite set, the order type determines the cardinality, but not conversely: sets of a particular infinite cardinality can have well-orders of many different types (see § Natural numbers, below, for an example).
[src:ordinal-arithmetic/well-order] For a countably infinite set, the set of possible order types is uncountable.
